issue.title: Prevent tiles from being cached by large-image
issue.body:
The large-image package caches tiles by default. Whenever a tile is retrieved, it is also put in a cache for faster retrieval in the future. Because we use each tile only once, we should disable the cache (if possible).

The caching is not a problem for us, because the cache is only kept for the current slide. The cache is deleted when we process the next slide.

Related to https://github.com/girder/large_image/issues/985.

issue.title: How disable TileSource cache
issue.body:
Hello, I love using large-image for my machine learning projects with digital pathology images. I have run into a problem where memory consumption continues to increase as I get more tiles from the image. For my long model-training jobs, this has ballooned to over 600 GB of RAM. After debugging, I learned about the cache that TileSource instances use.

Is there a supported API to disable the cache?

At the moment, I am using `tile_source.cache._Cache__maxsize = 0` , which works great for me (when the caching object is from `cachetools`).

I have also considered using `tile_source.cache.clear()` after tile reads, but I would prefer a solution that disables caching globally or at the TileSource level.

issue.title: Prevent tiles from being cached by large-image
issue.body:
The large-image package caches tiles by default. Whenever a tile is retrieved, it is also put in a cache for faster retrieval in the future. Because we use each tile only once, we should disable the cache (if possible).

The caching is not a problem for us, because the cache is only kept for the current slide. The cache is deleted when we process the next slide.

Related to https://github.com/girder/large_image/issues/985.

issue.title: How disable TileSource cache
issue.body:
Hello, I love using large-image for my machine learning projects with digital pathology images. I have run into a problem where memory consumption continues to increase as I get more tiles from the image. For my long model-training jobs, this has ballooned to over 600 GB of RAM. After debugging, I learned about the cache that TileSource instances use.

Is there a supported API to disable the cache?

At the moment, I am using `tile_source.cache._Cache__maxsize = 0` , which works great for me (when the caching object is from `cachetools`).

I have also considered using `tile_source.cache.clear()` after tile reads, but I would prefer a solution that disables caching globally or at the TileSource level.

issue.title: Prevent tiles from being cached by large-image
issue.body:
The large-image package caches tiles by default. Whenever a tile is retrieved, it is also put in a cache for faster retrieval in the future. Because we use each tile only once, we should disable the cache (if possible).

The caching is not a problem for us, because the cache is only kept for the current slide. The cache is deleted when we process the next slide.

Related to https://github.com/girder/large_image/issues/985.

issue.title: How disable TileSource cache
issue.body:
Hello, I love using large-image for my machine learning projects with digital pathology images. I have run into a problem where memory consumption continues to increase as I get more tiles from the image. For my long model-training jobs, this has ballooned to over 600 GB of RAM. After debugging, I learned about the cache that TileSource instances use.

Is there a supported API to disable the cache?

At the moment, I am using `tile_source.cache._Cache__maxsize = 0` , which works great for me (when the caching object is from `cachetools`).

I have also considered using `tile_source.cache.clear()` after tile reads, but I would prefer a solution that disables caching globally or at the TileSource level.

issue.title: Prevent tiles from being cached by large-image
issue.body:
The large-image package caches tiles by default. Whenever a tile is retrieved, it is also put in a cache for faster retrieval in the future. Because we use each tile only once, we should disable the cache (if possible).

The caching is not a problem for us, because the cache is only kept for the current slide. The cache is deleted when we process the next slide.

Related to https://github.com/girder/large_image/issues/985.
